The latest recording of Cuban drummer and percussionist Dafnis Prieto: “Cantar” has been released few months ago. The Grammy winner on this project, is collaborating with with another Grammy winner: Brazilian singer Luciana Souza, woodwinds player Peter Apfelbaum, Martin Bejerano on piano and Matt Brewer on bass.
The album is released on Dafnis own label: Dafnison Music. A little fado, a little Brazilian folklore, a little jazz, a lot of listening pleasure time for this album. 
Looking for a gift to the music lovers in your life… 
Cantar is a good option. The cut is: “Sueño de Amor”

Italian composer and guitarist Giuseppe Pucciarelli has released his 3rd album “Uplift” under “The Pucciarelli Group” on Ubuntu Music label.
Pucciarelli has been studying music and classical guitar since he was a child and keeps on studying and learning to create original compositions. On Uplift, he sources his inspiration into harmony and rhythm combinations that the “Pat Metheny Group” has pioneered since the early 1980’s. 
The group’s osmosis is obvious, each member is a virtuoso in his own right.
It is a great listening pleasure. Giuseppe Pucciarelli is on guitar, Ergio Valente on piano, Aldo Capasso on bass and Marco Gagliano on drums.

Talented musicians from the French West Indies are legion, music there is a way of life yet, few have enjoyed an international career such as Mino Cinelu, Mario Canonge or Alain Jean-Marie. 
Saxophonist Jacques Schwarz-Bart is another one with international recognition. After music studies at the Berklee college of Music in Boston, Jacques has stayed and work with local artists such as Meshell N’degeocello or Roy Hargrove.
While mastering the techniques of the saxophone, it is with his original compositions that Jacques Schwarz-Bart shines, inspired by the rhythms and sensitivities of his native island: Guadeloupe.
Over a year ago, Jacques released his album : “Sone Ka-La 2” on Enja records.
Jacques is on saxophone, Malika Tirolien on vocals, Gregory Privat on keyboards, Reggie Washington on bass, Arnaud Dolmen on drums and Sonny Troupe on Ka-drum.
At the exception of Reggie who is American, all musicians are from the French West Indies. The cut is “Konk a Lambi”

After Jeff Beck, another passing is hurting bad.
David Crosby with his mix of folk and prog rock had been on the playlists of my teenage years.
My favorite album: “If I could only remember my name” was 52 years ago and I still spin it up today.
I will always remember your name!

#davidcrosby #instarock #instafolk

The bridge between David Crosby and jazz, is an easy one to cross.
In 1968, Crosby wrote and composed Guinnevere for the debut album of “Crosby, Still and Nash”. Two years later, Miles Davis bewitched by the melody, recorded his interpretation during the “Bitches Brew” sessions, but was not part of the tunes line up of the original release. It is 9 years later that Davis version was released on “Circle in the Round” then in 1998 with the release of the complete “Bitches Brew” sessions by Sony Music.
Fast forward to 2020, trumpetist Christian Scott decided to arrange his own version of the Crosby classic, recorded live at the Blue Note in New York and released in the summer of 2020 for the album “Axiom” on Ropeadope Records.
Scott is on trumpet, Lawrence Fields on electric piano, Kris Funn on bass, Corey Fonville on drums, Weedie Braimah on percussion and Elena Pinderhughes on flute.

Staying with Christian Scott, underlining his talent to bring jazz into new spheres, he did it again five years ago, partnering with other talented musicians of his generation for a special band named R+R=Now.
The idea grew in the mind of Robert Glasper after working on the music for a Nina Simone documentary where the singer famously stated that her music, her songs are a reflection of the time in which she lived, asking other artists to do the same. Fast forward to our time, Glasper took her position at heart and assembled a group of innovative artists to work on a music reflecting the time, good and bad that is ours today.
Robert Glasper and Christian Scott are joined by bassist Derrick Hodge, Drummer Justin Tyson, Saxophonist Terrace Martin and keyboards player Taylor McFerrin.
“Reflect + Respond = Now” is a band on a mission to blur the borders of genres so every one can find their groovy theme. R&B, Neo Soul, 
Nu jazz or other sticker do not fully apply. It is fresh, contemporary and is a reflection of our today’s life.
The album name is “Collagically Speaking” released on Blue Note in 2019, the cut is “Resting Warrior”

12 years ago, drummer Omar Hakim and pianist Rachel Z created a trio: “The Trio of Oz” adding bassist Maeve Royce and recorded an album on Ozmosis records.
Both, Omar and Rachel are veterans of the jazz scene, having contributed to the genre for over 35 years in multiple trends from classic bop to fusion with escapades in pop and rock.
The trio of Oz is contemporary with touches from all over the music spectrum.
The cut is “Bizzard Love Triangle”

He mastered the art of the love ballad.
What a life.

It has been four decades since Kenny Barron last solo piano recording.
At 79, Barron shows he has not lost any of his talent, releasing the difficult exercise of a solo album “The Source” on artwork records.
The cut is “Dolores Street, SF” first recorded 50 years ago on “Sunset to Dawn” with his band, a fantastic album on Muse records.

#kennybarron #solopiano #pianojazz #instajazz #jazzkaleidoscope #jazzmusic #jazzmusician #artworkrecords

Like a jazz dandy, Australian musician John McAll is taking his time to craft new moods and fresh composition to constantly surprise his audience. Nothing is left to chance, his music is sophisticated, intriguing and groovy at times, with some references from the 1950’s and 60’s floating around it.
John McAll is marrying to perfection the traditional piano, bass and drums to a brass section for his new album. The McAll name is very familiar to music aficionados Down Under, but if you are yet to listen to his music in the northern part of the world, I invite you to discover it.
The new album is “Pass the Rainbow” it will be released on March 10.
The cut is “Undercurrents”, a nice preview of what’s to come.
John is on piano, Nic Ryan Glenie on trumpet, Anton Delecca on saxophone, Paddy Fitzgerald on bass, Aaron McCoullough on drums and James Macaulay on trombone.

From musician to legend, Wayne Shorter has marked contemporary jazz with creative ideas never heard before on the saxophone. I first saw him live in Paris with Weather Report at the end of the 1970’s for the promotion of “Heavy Weather” and will always remember the back and forth between him and Joe Zawinul.
Wayne has left us today. His contribution to music and our personal joy is huge.

#wayneshorter #instajazz #jazzkaleidoscope #jazzmusic #jazzmusician #saxophonejazz

I was asked recently if I knew a French guitarist by the name of Anthony Winzenrieth and was encouraged to listen to his music.
I did, and discovered an album named “Corpus”. A real gem.
The pleasure of anticipating the release of a new album from an artist you like is a big part of my passion for music, the discovery of new music you enjoy from an artist you did not know is equally as joyful.
This album makes a lot of space to harmonies exploration and story telling. Released 5 years ago, it is easy to listen to and sourced in classic quartets, the patterns are contemporary and can be complex at time with surprising outcome.
I love it and am pleased to have discovered this hidden gem. The cut is “I’m Strong”.
Anthony Winzenrieth is on guitar, Leonardo Montana on piano, Florent Nisse on bass and Antoine Paganotti on drums. saxophonist Irving Acao is a guest artist on a couple of tunes like “La Marseillaise” the French National Anthem which interpretation is simply brilliant and unexpected.

The story of pianist Malcolm Braff is fascinating.
Born in Brazil to Scandinavian parents and then raised in Senegal and Switzerland, Malcolm has accumulated a wealth of memories and an expanded cultural outlook, which can be found in his music.
23 years ago, Malcolm released “The Preacher” on blue note.
The cut is “Budum Budum”. Malcolm Braff is on piano, Matthieu Michel on trumpet, Yaya Ouattara on percussion, Olivier Clerc on drums and Banz Oester on bass.

Sixun had not released new music since their 2009 “Live in Marciac”.
Few months ago, the band got back in studio to record a new album “Unixsity” on Dreyfus Jazz.
Very active in the 80s and 90s, members of the band went on to work on solo projects but seem to reunite from time to time for the pleasure of their fans, enjoying the uplifting brand of music which is the trade mark of Sixun. It has been 38 years since the formation of the band, and Sixun has not lost any of their enthusiasm working together, you can hear it.
The cut is “Faith”.
Alain Debiossat is on Saxophone, Jean Pierre Como on keyboards, Louis Winsberg on guitar, Michel Alibo on bass, Paco sery on drums, Stephane Edouard on percussion, with the voice of special guest Cynthia Abraham.

When an important artist has passed away, sadness quickly makes space for the sudden desire to listen to music you have not played for a long while.
Searching Wayne Shorter’s albums and those who he was a co-leader to the ones he was a guest, you find yourself with dozens and dozens of recordings you are rediscovering. From the Jazz Messengers to Miles Davis to Weather Report with a fun period bringing contribution to the music of Joni Mitchell or his participation to the music of James Newton Howard for Glengarry Glen Ross movie score, the opportunities to listen to the art of Wayne Shorter are immense.
I pulled a CD I had not listened to for a long time: Michel Petrucciani “Power of Three” with Jim Hall and Wayne Shorter, recorded live at the Montreux Jazz Festival in 1986. Claude Nobs the late founder of the festival has said that every time he sees Wayne playing the saxophone on stage is a magical experience.
Wayne’s phrasing on the saxophone is unique and recognizable. The cut is “Limbo” composed by Wayne Shorter who is on tenor saxophone, Michel Petrucciani on piano and Jim Hall on guitar.

The name Carles Benavent May not ring a bell for many on this side of the Atlantic. The Spanish bassist from Barcelona has recorded numerous albums on the Flamenco genre yet, his credentials in jazz are impressive.
Recording alongside Chick Corea in 1982 for the “Touchstone” album.
Part of the Quincy Jones and Miles Davis band for the 1991 “Live in Montreux”. In 1992, he recorded with Arif Mardin and Vince Mendoza for the “Jazzpaña” project. Performed with Pat Metheny in 2003 to just mention a few interesting gigs. I first read his credit on a recording of Paco de Lucia with whom Carles Benavent worked extensively.
Few months ago, Carles went back in the studio and worked on very interesting compositions recorded under the name “Belle Solitude” for Bebyne records.
The cut is “Alegria de Júlia”. Carles is on bass and guitar, Jordi Bonell on guitar, Roger Blavia and Aleix Tobias on drums and percussion.

British saxophonist Binker Golding has gotten us used to the duo “Binker & Moses” with drummer Moses Boyd, an unusual saxophone and drums duo exploring avant-garde jazz. 
From times to times, Binker Golding welcomes a more traditional band to enrich his compositions with new and different sounds. This is the case on his last summer release :”Dream Like a Dogwood Wild Boy” on Gearbox Records, where Binker infuses some country music sounds to his jazz.
The cut is: “Howling And Drinking In God’s Own Country”.
Binker Golding is on tenor saxophone, Daniel Casamir on bass, Billy Adamson on guitar, Sam Jones on drums and Sarah Tandy on piano.

Last night, PBS did broadcast the 2023 Gershwin prize for popular songs from the Library of Congress. The recipient, Joni Mitchell was awarded and celebrated by artists, Annie Lennox, Brandi Carlile, Graham Nash and many others with of course Herbie Hancock.
The show reminded us how important the meaning of her songs, how talented the music compositions, and how emotional her voice is.
Billy Joel mentioned that Joni was fearless in her music experimentation, infusing jazz to her compositions in the 1970s.
The cut is “Tea Leaf Prophecy” from Hancock “River, The Joni Letters” released in 2007 on Verve records.
Herbie Hancock is on piano, Wayne Shorter on saxophone, Dave Holland on bass, Lionel Loueke on guitar, Vinnie Colaiuta on drums and the beautiful voice of Joni Mitchell.

After a long hiatus from posting, I am back ;)
Taking advantage of being in Las Vegas for a few days, I went to see U2 at the new SPHERE venue. The experience was so spectacular that I felt compelled to post about it.
Music is such an important part of our lives, jazz and its sub-genres have been my areas of preference but I was not insensitive to the pop and rock of the 1980s, U2, Simply Red, Depeche Mode, etc.
The staying power of bands like the Stones or U2 is rare and a testimony of the quality and meanings their music represent to more than one generation. U2 at the Sphere was an incredible show combining the sound with a visual production of the highest quality.
Lady Gaga made a surprise appearance and sung a couple of tunes with the band. It was two and a half hours of pure delight in a one of a kind venue that seats over 18,000 people without counting those standing around the stage.
#U2 #instarock #instapop #spherelasvegas

Last week, out of the blue, the tune “Fickle Funk” from Chick Corea popped in my mind. I did not remember the title, just knew it was from Chick. I hadn’t listen to it for a very very long time. I thought it might have been from the “Elektric Band” and I started to listen to all of them and realized it was earlier and it was even released before “Friends” on the “Secret  Agent” album from 1978 on Polydor. 45 years later, this tune has not aged a bit, and I have a great pleasure rediscovering it.
Joe Farrell is on saxophone, Allen Vizzutti on flugelhorn, Bunny Brunel on bass, Airto Moreira on percussion and Chick on electric piano.
#chickcorea #joefarrell #allenvizzutti #bunnybrunel #airtomoreira #polydorrecords #instajazz #jazzmusic #jazzmusician #jazzmusicians #jazzfussion #jazzrock #electricpianoforsale

Creed Taylor has produced a lot of gems with his own label CTI.
One of them is “Sky Dive” from Freddie Hubbard recorded in 1972 with an all star lineup.
When I listen to those 50 years old recordings, I am fascinated by the work on the arrangements and orchestration from Don Sebesky. Like Gil Evans with Miles Davis, Hubbard and Sebesky have recorded some landmark music I listen to with great pleasure 50 years later.

Recorded in 2022 Norway, her inspiration is hard to define but there is no doubt fellow saxophonist Jan Garbarek music has been playing often in Mette Henriette’s home.
The album is “Drifting” a trio with Henriette on saxophone, Johan Lindvall on piano and Judith Hamann on cello.
The cut is “I Villvind”.

This is “I got my Mojo workin” remixed by Grand Master Duda who put a modern touch to the 1957 rendition of the tune from Muddy Waters.
With such rhythm, and the sun shining in New York this morning, the day is going to be great!

We are in 1976. There is a drought in the Western world that summer, with some of the highest temperatures ever recorded then.
In New York, Stanley Clarke is recording his 4th solo album: “School Days”. In this session, Stanley has invited John McLaughlin and Milt Holland to record “Desert Song”.
Milt is on percussion, John on acoustic guitar and Stanley on double bass.

#Stanleyclarke #johnmclaughlin #miltholland #1976 #instajazz #jazzmusic #contemporaryjazz #jazzmusician #jazzfusion 
@stanleyclarke @officialjohnmclaughlin

While many had discovered Brad Mehldau in the early 90s, my first CD from Brad was “the art of the trio volume one” released in 1996 on Warner Bros.
Joining him are Jorge Rossy on drums and Larry Grenadier on bass.
We now know from various interviews and his discography since, that Brad’s influences are divers, the pop of the 60s, the prog-rock of the 70s and 80s, some classical music and Keith Jarrett.
On the art of the trio volume one, Brad has recorded his version of my favorite song from The Beatles: “Blackbird”. I just love this interpretation.
